## Attempts to develop a quantum mechanical theory of cosmology

### Background

The pursuit of [quantum cosmology](/Quantum_field_theory) is, in essence, the theoretical physicist's rather audacious attempt to craft a quantum mechanical blueprint for the entire universe. It’s a grand, perhaps foolish, endeavor aimed at unraveling the deepest mysteries of our cosmic origins, particularly those initial, unfathomable moments that precede and include the [Big Bang](/Big_Bang).

Our current, rather elegant, description of the universe's evolution, [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein)'s [general theory of relativity](/General_theory_of_relativity) (GTR), functions brilliantly for the most part. It maps out the cosmic dance with remarkable precision. However, like a worn-out map that ends at the edge of the known world, it falters when we approach the primordial [gravitational singularity](/Gravitational_singularity) or the infinitesimally brief expanse of the [Planck time](/Planck_time). Here, relativity’s pronouncements become whispers, then silence. It's at these boundaries, where space and time themselves warp and break, that a truly fundamental theory must step in. This necessitates a framework that can reconcile the colossal, the gravitational, with the impossibly small, the quantum. This is the chasm [quantum cosmology](/Quantum_field_theory) seeks to bridge.

Approaches to this monumental task are varied, each a brushstroke on a canvas too vast to comprehend. There's [loop quantum cosmology](/Loop_quantum_cosmology), a descendant of [loop quantum gravity](/Loop_quantum_gravity), which attempts to quantize spacetime itself. Then there's [string theory](/String_theory), proposing that fundamental entities are not point-like particles but vibrating strings in higher dimensions. And [causal set theory](/Causal_sets), which posits that spacetime is fundamentally discrete, built from fundamental events linked by causal relationships. Each is a different lens, a different gamble, in the attempt to capture the universe's quantum heartbeat.

In this quantum cosmological view, the universe is no longer a mere stage of classical [spacetime](/Spacetime). Instead, it is envisioned as a singular, all-encompassing [wave function](/Wave_function). Imagine the cosmos itself, reduced to a probabilistic wave, its properties and evolution governed by the arcane rules of quantum mechanics. It's a profound shift in perspective, from a deterministic unfolding of events to a realm of inherent uncertainty and potentiality.

