The universe, even in its nascent, quantum state, is expected to exhibit profound [symmetries](/Symmetry_physics). These aren't just aesthetic preferences of the cosmos; they are deeply ingrained principles that dictate its behavior. From the fundamental symmetries of [quantum mechanics](/Quantum_mechanics) like [C-symmetry](/Charge_conjugation), [P-symmetry](/Parity_(physics)), and [T-symmetry](/T-symmetry), which govern charge, parity, and time reversal respectively, to the bedrock of relativistic invariance embodied by [Lorentz symmetry](/Lorentz_symmetry) and [Poincaré symmetry](/Poincar%C3%A9_symmetry), these symmetries provide the underlying structure. [Gauge symmetry](/Gauge_symmetry_(mathematics)), particularly in the form of [Yang–Mills theory](/Yang%E2%80%93Mills_theory), is the language through which fundamental forces are described. The way these symmetries manifest, or fail to manifest, through mechanisms like [explicit symmetry breaking](/Explicit_symmetry_breaking) and [spontaneous symmetry breaking](/Spontaneous_symmetry_breaking), dictates the very character of the universe we observe. Even concepts like [Noether charge](/Noether_charge) and [topological charge](/Topological_charge) hint at deeper, conserved quantities that might have played crucial roles in the universe's initial moments.

