To probe the quantum nature of the universe, theoretical physicists employ a formidable arsenal of mathematical and conceptual [tools](/Quantum_gravity). [Feynman diagrams](/Feynman_diagram), those elegant scribbles, visualize particle interactions, a crucial technique for understanding the interplay of forces. The [Path Integral Formulation](/Path_Integral_Formulation), pioneered by Feynman, offers a way to calculate probabilities by summing over all possible histories. Concepts like [renormalization](/Renormalization) are essential for taming infinities that plague calculations in [quantum field theory](/Quantum_field_theory). [Effective field theories](/Effective_field_theory) allow us to focus on the relevant physics at specific energy scales, while the [background field method](/Background_field_method) and [BRST quantization](/BRST_quantization) are sophisticated techniques for dealing with gauge theories. Understanding the [vacuum state](/Vacuum_state) is paramount, as it's far from empty in quantum mechanics, teeming with virtual particles and quantum fluctuations. The [partition function](/Partition_function_(quantum_field_theory)) provides a complete statistical description of a quantum system, and [correlation functions](/Correlation_function_(quantum_field_theory)) reveal how different parts of the system are related. Even the seemingly esoteric [Wightman axioms](/Wightman_axioms) provide a rigorous foundation for [quantum field theory](/Quantum_field_theory).

### Equations

