*   [Schwinger-Dyson equation](/Schwinger-Dyson_equation)
*   [Renormalization group equation](/Renormalization_group)

The language of physics, especially at this fundamental level, is mathematics. Central to quantum cosmology are equations that attempt to describe the universe's quantum state. The [Wheeler–DeWitt equation](/Wheeler%E2%80%93DeWitt_equation), for instance, is a cornerstone of canonical quantum gravity, attempting to describe the wave function of the universe itself, but it famously faces challenges with the concept of time. Relativistic wave equations like the [Dirac equation](/Dirac_equation) and the [Klein–Gordon equation](/Klein%E2%80%93Gordon_equation) are fundamental for describing relativistic particles, and their application at the cosmological scale is a subject of ongoing research. Equations governing [Proca](/Proca_action) fields and the more general [Bargmann–Wigner equations](/Bargmann%E2%80%93Wigner_equations) also play roles in describing fundamental particles. The [Schwinger-Dyson equation](/Schwinger-Dyson_equation) provides a non-perturbative approach to quantum field theory, and the [Renormalization group equation](/Renormalization_group) describes how physical parameters change with energy scale, crucial for understanding physics across vastly different cosmic epochs.

### Standard Model

*   [Quantum electrodynamics](/Quantum_electrodynamics)
*   [Electroweak interaction](/Electroweak_interaction)
*   [Quantum chromodynamics](/Quantum_chromodynamics)
*   [Higgs mechanism](/Higgs_mechanism)

While quantum cosmology aims for a theory of everything, it must also engage with our current best description of fundamental particles and forces: the [Standard Model](/Standard_Model). This model, with its pillars of [quantum electrodynamics](/Quantum_electrodynamics) (describing light and matter interactions), [quantum chromodynamics](/Quantum_chromodynamics) (governing the strong nuclear force), and the [electroweak interaction](/Electroweak_interaction) (unifying electricity and magnetism with the weak force), provides the known ingredients of the universe. The [Higgs mechanism](/Higgs_mechanism), responsible for giving particles mass, is also a critical component that any quantum cosmological theory must encompass or supersede.

### Incomplete theories

*   [String theory](/String_theory)
*   [Supersymmetry](/Supersymmetry)
*   [Technicolor](/Technicolor_(physics))
*   [Theory of everything](/Theory_of_everything)
*   [Quantum gravity](/Quantum_gravity)

The quest for a quantum theory of cosmology is inextricably linked to the development of [incomplete theories](/Theory_of_everything) that aim to unify the fundamental forces and particles. [String theory](/String_theory), with its elegant yet complex framework, and [supersymmetry](/Supersymmetry), proposing a symmetry between bosons and fermions, are major contenders. [Technicolor](/Technicolor_(physics)) offers an alternative mechanism for electroweak symmetry breaking. Ultimately, the goal is a [Theory of Everything](/Theory_of_everything), a single, coherent framework that describes all physical phenomena, and the development of [quantum gravity](/Quantum_gravity) is the most significant hurdle in this pursuit.

